One did not see signs of disapproval or embarrassment on the respective stages, and neither on the social media platforms where the two clips swiftly went viral.
Viral is the word. In this day and age, it describes a picture, video, graphic or other piece of information circulated rapidly and widely from one internet user to another.
The original term describes something caused by or relating to a virus. That should be the operative term in this context. Emergence of Covid-19 makes us all acutely aware of what a virus is, how fast it spreads, and the death and destruction it can visit upon civilisation.
Our political leaders in their element visit on us verbal pandemics. Out of their unbridled mouths come toxic words and utterances that are not just rude and primitive, but ultimately divide the people and incite hatred and violence.
Now, this is not just about Ms Jumwa and Mr Sifuna, at best excitable chatterboxes who are mere cogs in the wheel.
It is also not just about the Msambweni Parliamentary seat. This is a by-election that would ordinarily pass unnoticed on the national news radar but for the fact that it provides the stage for a titanic battle between the Uhuru-Raila forces and the Ruto brigade.



